&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Hello Niels,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; As far as I can see, these are the ways a crawl can pause itself
&gt; &gt; spontaneously
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; - with the RuntimeLimitEnforcer processor
&gt; &gt; - LowDiskPauseProcessor or DiskSpaceMonitor
&gt; &gt; - in case of a serious error like OutOfMemoryError
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; If you don&#39;t have any of those modules configured (none of them are by
&gt; &gt; default), then it must be the serious error case. There should be a stack
&gt; &gt; trace in your heritrix_out.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; If it&#39;s OOME then you can bump up your heap size or reduce the number of
&gt; &gt; toe threads in your job.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Noah
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; On Wed, Jul 31, 2013 at 11:21 AM, Niels &lt;niels.van.hecke@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Hello,
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I&#39;ve attempted running Heritrix 3.1.1 multiple times now and have found
&gt; &gt; &gt; that at irregular intervals, the crawler engine goes into the &#39;pausing&#39;
&gt; &gt; &gt; state and then just sits there. I don&#39;t know why, I cannot predict
&gt; when,
&gt; &gt; &gt; and I don&#39;t know how. My logs at the time show a fair amount of issues
&gt; with
&gt; &gt; &gt; the MirrorWritterProcessor, but all of the errors are caught and there
&gt; is
&gt; &gt; &gt; no indication that the server is going to be kicked into the paused
&gt; state.
&gt; &gt; &gt; Is there some sort of feature that causes this that is documented
&gt; anywhere?
&gt; &gt; &gt; I don&#39;t see any within my config file.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
